Hi,

I stumbled upon an inconsistency in the usage of Cocos2d between the HTML5 engine and Cocos2d-x with JS bindings. I'm using Cocos2d-x 3.10.

After creating a shader and setting it to a cc.Node, you can update the uniforms it uses using `cc.GLProgram` and its `setUniformLocationWithXXX` functions. This works properly with HTML5, but won't work when the game is run with Cocos2d-x on native platforms (At least iOS/OS X, not tested with other platforms but it's unlikely to work properly). 

To workaround this issue, you have to use `getGLProgramState`, which is provided by JS bindings of Cocos2d-x. I got the idea by looking at [this thread](http://discuss.cocos2d-x.org/t/basic-shader-help/16533/13).
## Steps to reproduce

I made a **[repository with the source code](https://github.com/4ian/Cocos2d-shaders-test)** of Hello world, plus a shader with a uniform being updated. If you look at [the source code](https://github.com/4ian/Cocos2d-shaders-test/blob/master/src/app.js), you can see that to make it work on all platforms, I had to use this:

``` js
// 3rd gotcha: shader uniforms should be updated using getGLProgramState with Cocos2d-x.
        // Calling setUniformLocationWithXXX only works with HTML5.
        if (this.sprite.getGLProgramState) {
            this.sprite.getGLProgramState().setUniformFloat("u_value", Math.random());
        } else {
            this._shader.setUniformLocationWith1f(this._valueUniform, Math.random());
        }
```

The Readme in the repository should be enough to let you try the game. Let me know if something is unclear!
I guess that setUniformLocationWith1f should either be updated to work on Cocos2d-x, or at least have a big **warning** added to the documentation. :wink:

